column168: An audible release was observed from PROX 35680 in the Roseville yard on 6/5/2018. The A end liquid  valve was in the open position and the plug was less then tool-tight. There was a liquid release at the  liquid valve plug threads. The valve was closed and the release was stopped. The plug was cross  threaded and is damaged, it can only be engaged 1 turn. The A end liquid valve plug and plug (outlet)  flange will be replaced by a mobile repair crew.

column168: When forklift operator was loading freight into trailer he pulled out of the pallet and then went to adjust it better. While doing so he lifted the forkblades a bit too high and as a result struck the drum that was staged on the pallet. The drum was laid on its side to minimize the release and patched with drum putty. The spilled material was cleaned with absorbent material and placed into a recovery container as was the punctured drum.
column169: Forklift operators need to pay attention to the clearances of their forklifts including the forkblades to prevent these types of unintentional releases from occurring.

column168: Driver was delivering gasoline and had finished offloading all of compartment #1. Driver removed dust cap from compartment #2 and fuel sprayed out onto the ground. The driver immediately shut down the API valve to stop the flow.
column169: Driver failed to follow policy and had opened the API valve on compartment #2 before he had a hose connected to this fitting. Driver is being re-trained in policy.

column168: On June 3, 2018 the Hawaiian Airlines (HA) interline baggage service at the Honolulu  International Airport received baggage from Delta Airlines (DL) for transfer to a HA flight 142  bound for Hilo (ITO), Hawaii.  The baggage accepted for transfer to HA was a cooler containing dry ice.  The quantity of dry ice was listed as 5.5 lbs/2.5 kg or less. There was no failure of the package.      During the off-loading of the baggage it was discovered that the cooler with the dry ice had been  transported to ITO without the proper Notification to Pilot In Command (NOPIC).  HA procedures  state that Interline DG is prohibited.
column169: Root Cause of the incident was that the Company's policy on the acceptance of  dangerous goods was not properly followed. It is the policy (Cargo Manual) 7.1.1(G) of Hawaiian Airlines that the acceptance of dangerous goods via interline transfer is prohibited. Load-master for the flight received a Letter of Counseling for not being aware of DG interline being loaded on his flight.   HA will review the policy and procedures for interline baggage transfer to ensure that the policy is clear. The policy will be reviewed with all responsible personnel.

On June 4, 2018, personnel at CSX’s Knoxville Yard, reported a suspect release from UTLX 670519, a loaded tank car of Styrene Monomer.  The car was isolated and Lyondell Chemical was notified via CHEMTREC Report 2018-0604-00035.  Marion Environmental, Inc. (MEI), a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the car was actively releasing product at the threaded connection between the tank car and the tank car’s liquid line valve. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. Contractor personnel tightened the threaded connection of the valve to the car which stopped the release. The car was held from transportation pending a One Time Movement Approval from the FRA. NRC notification 1214154. The system will not allow this to be entered into the correct box

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Prior to loading driver checked internal pressure of vehicle and determined it to be 170 psi.  During loading the pressure elevated within the container and ultimately reached 245 psi once the loading was completed.  Higher pressures are expected at this location during the summer due to the elevated temperatures.  This facility does not provide for a vapor return so drivers maintain watch on the pressure gauge to ensure pressure levels do not exceed the CT operating pressure.  Once loading was completed the driver proceeded away from the loading rack enroute for the facility scale.  After clearing the scale by approximately 15 yards, the CT rear relief device activated releasing pressure for approximately 30 seconds and reclosed.  Pressure in the tanker had reduced below 200 psi at time of re-inspection after closure.
column169: Facility should allow for vapor return during high temperature seasons. Carrier may adjust maximum operating pressure during high temperature periods to create a larger buffer zone.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: At 2018 ERTS was contacted by Jeff Bowen of XPO Logistics NCH about a cargo release. It was reported that due to a forklift accident approximately 1 pound of UN2680,8,II Lithium Hydroxide released from a 50 pound bag. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the trailer and dock area. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and it was determined a contractor needed to be sent. HEPACO arrived to the site and at 0025 ERTS was notified that HEPACO had left the site and successfully cleaned up the spill of Lithium Hydroxide. All material that had been released was gathered and put in a 55 gal poly drum along with pads, PPE, and damaged bag. The undamaged material was re-packed onto 3 pallets. There is no further cleanup needed.

At 0336 ERTS was contacted by Michael Kostecka of XPO Logistics XGH2 about a cargo release. It was reported that due to improper loading approximately 1 pint UN1866,3,III Polynt Composites "DO base white sanding" released from a 55 gal metal drum. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the trailer. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and he felt comfortable cleaning the release with granular absorbents and the proper PPE. The released product and 55 gal metal drum were placed in a 85 gal metal drum and staged in OS&D. No more cleanup is needed at this time.

column168: At approximately 8:15am on Monday, 6/11/18, a company distillates driver was traveling Westbound on Scottsville-Mumford Road.  Our driver encountered an intersection with Wheatland Ctr. Road at which he was presented with a flashing yellow light.  A driver in a medical transport van was traveling Northbound on Wheatland Ctr. Road at the same time and had a flashing red light and stop signs with notations indicating that the traffic on the opposing road did not have to stop.  To the best of our knowledge, the medical transport van did not stop for the stop signs at the intersection and ran into the cab of the company 10-wheel fuel truck.  The 10-wheeler driver attempted to retain control of his truck, but such significant damage was done upon impact that it caused him to veer off the road as the truck flipped onto the passenger side.  The truck slid into a tree at which point, it dislodge the tank level sensor, releasing the fuel inside of that compartment onto the ground surrounding the truck.
column169: The level probe is protected by the top rails of the tank. Had the top rails been made of a stronger material of construction, the high level probe might have remained intake during impact.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: RONALD SHERMAN RECEIVED A RADIO CALL AT APPROXIMATELY 23:45 06-04-2018, RONALD SHERMAN THEN PROCEEDED TO DON HIS PPE (BOOTS, GLOVES, APRON, GOGGLES) AND RESPOND TO THE SITUATION HE WAS CALLED TO. HE ARRIVED AT PD-9 DOOR 58 AND BROUGHT HIS SPILL CART AS CLOSE AS POSSIBLE TO THE SPILL SITE, AND SET UP A 15 FOOT HOT ZONE AND PROCEEDED TO UTILIZE HIS DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS TO DETERMINE HIS PLAN OF ACTION, HE DETERMINED THE LEAKING PACKAGE WAS MARKED WITH FLAMMABLE LIQUID 3.1, SO HE ATTEMPTED TO CLEAN THE SPILL USING CLAY BASED ABSORBENT AND NONE SPARKING EQUIPMENT (PLASTIC BROOM AND PAN) THEN CONTAINERIZED THE PARCEL INTO A SPILL TOTE FOR FURTHER TRANSPORTATION BACK TO THE DMP AND THERE JOSEPH KRUEGER TOOK OVER THE PROCESSING OF THE MATERIAL. JOSEPH OPENED THE PARCEL AND PROCESSED THE CONTENTS INTO 2 GREEN BAGS AND DETERMINED THAT THE NOZZLE ON THE FIVE GALLON PAIL WAS FAULTY, AND THAT IT WAS LIKELY DAMAGED IN TRANSIT THROUGH THE FACILITY EITHER THROUGH HUMAN ERROR OR CONVEYANCE FAILURES.

column43: EPOXY RESIN PART A, PART B
column168: The shipment was accepted by Worldwide Flight Services agent on Friday, 22JUN2018. Shipment was booked to fly on LH467/ 23JUN2018, SAN-FRA-DME. Shipment was declared as Civil Aircraft Parts. On Saturday, 23JUN2018, WFS warehouse agent was inspecting cargo before loading on Lufthansa Pallet, and was referencing the commodity to the shipment itself and realized the shipment descriptions did not match. Upon further inspection, the warehouse agent came to the conclusion that this shipment was in fact not Civil Aircraft Parts, but in actuality, Undeclared Dangerous Goods in the form of Resins both Parts A and Parts B. WFS agents were advised to contact FAA, customer was notified of rejection, and customer has attempted to pick up shipment from our warehouse, however we are still holding-The shipment until further advised by the FAA.

column26: 1762 FIRST STREET C37 AM COMBS BLDG
column168: Package was received at our shipping dock from a customer with a cockpit voice/data recorder(CVR) inside the package. The 90 day beacon on the CVR contains 1.75g lithium metal content so this was a lithium metal battery packaged in equipment shipment. Package had no markings that it was a dangerous goods/hazardous materials shipment. Our shipping department personnel unpackaged the unit and delivered the unit to our repair department. We notified the shipper they shipped a dangerous good without the proper labels and documentation and that they needed to remedy this in the future and that Universal Avionics was required to report the incident. There was no release.
column169: notify management when an incident occurs. We provided additional training to recognize when a hazardous material arrives without the appropriate markings or documentation and no release and to immediately report it to management so we can capture all the appropriate information in order to report the incident. We have also notified customers and dealers through newsletters, a notice on our customer website and a service bulletin about reshipping this particular product for repairs and the need to ship as dangerous goods/hazardous material.

column168: THE TRAILER FROM QUAD AVE LOCAL SORT 2169 CAME IN UNDER UPST367520. THE FT SUPERVISOR NOTICED THE LEAKING AND CALLED IN OVER THE RADIO FOR RESPONDER. AS WE WERE UNLOADING FROM IT, THERE WERE MULTIPLE PACKAGES HAD LEAKED ON FROM THE LEAKER. AT THAT POINT I MOVED THEM INTO DMP ON A IRREG TABLE. AFTER I OPENED UP THE ACTUAL LEAKER, I IMMEDIATELY NOTICED THE FLAMMABLE WARNING ON THE CONTAINER AS WELL AS STRONG ODOR (TOLERABLE) FROM THE PACKAGE. AFTER I LOOKED UP ON THE INTERNET FOR MSDS, AND READ THROUGH ALL OF THE SECTIONS. I NOTICED UNDER "SEC. 14 TRANSPORTATION", IT HAS THIS PRODUCT LABELED AS: DOT UN1133, ADHESIVES (CONTAINING A FLAMMABLE LIQUID), 3, III. AT THAT POINT, I CONTACTED THE HMSC FOR FURTHER INSTRUCTION AS HOW TO PROCEED. SINCE I AM AN ACCEPTANCE AUDITOR   RESPONDER.
column169: IF THIS ITEM SHOULD BE SHIPPING AS HAZMAT, PLEASE FOLLOW UP WITH THE SHIPPER TO REGULATE THIS ITEM AS PER DOT GUIDELINES. ALSO, AUDIT THIS SHIPPER'S PACKAGES BY OPENING THEM UP AT ORIGIN BUILDING FOR INSPECTION. JUST TO PREVENT UN-DECLARED HAZMAT TO ENTER INTO UPS SYSTEM WITHOUT AS KNOWING ABOUT IT.

column168: On 6/22/18, RDWY128285 was reported with a slow active leak by RDWY driver at BNSF San Bernardino, CA.  The trailer was moved to the containment pit for safety purposes.  YRC Chemical Helpline was contacted for assistance; Ocean Blue Environmental responded for remediation. Per the interior inspection, this was a mixed freight shipment originated Willow Springs, IL. The contractor advised the leak material was determined to be 2 gallon loss of SIKADOR 51 SL FLEXIBLE EPOXY CONTROL JOINT RESIN with a corrosive placard on the container. Per the investigation by the contractor, they determined the damaged 2 gallon container was previously damaged at origin and subsequently placed in the middle of the pallet in order to conceal the leak.  The load was remediated /over packed and removed by Ocean Blue Environmental. This incident is classified as shipper responsibility.
column169: BNSF LARS team has followed up with the shipper origin facility to discussed details of the incident.  The shipper should ensure that all containers with Hazardous Materials are properly loaded for transport and properly blocked and braced for unanticipated movement.

column168: On 6/1/18 at approximately 10:00 am a Venezia Transport tanker truck was getting set up to receive a load of heated coal tar. As the IMTT Chemical Operator was moving the fall protection ladder into place it accidentally struck the spiller pipe which in turn knocked the bucket, which hangs on the end of the arm, over causing coal tar to spill onto the side of the tanker truck. The IMTT Chemical Operator immediately contacted his supervisor who in turn contacted US Ecology(IMTT's OSRO) to clean up the side of the truck. When this was complete the loading . operation continued without incident.
column169: Upon investigation IMTT determined that the loading arm which was recently installed was not level and when the IMTT Chemical Operator went to move the fall protection stairs it struck the loading arm. The rack was taken out of service so the loading arm can be re-aligned. The rack is now back in service.

column168: On June 2, 2018 the Hawaiian Airlines (HA) cargo facility in Honolulu prepared a company material (COMAT) hazardous material shipment of a 1.4 kg (~34 cubic feet) compressed oxygen gas cylinder (~34 cubic feet) for transport to Kahului, Maui (OGG). There was no failure of the package. The proper Air Way Bill (AWB 03467656), dangerous goods checklist, shipper's declaration and Notification to Pilot in Command (NOPIC) were completed for the shipment and the documents were placed on the clipboard for HAZMAT shipment notification. The HAZMAT shipment was schedule flight on the next flight to Kahului. At approximately 14:53pm, the HA cargo runner picked up the HAZMAT shipment for delivery to the AC. The shipment was taken to the AC without the proper documentation (NOPIC) and loaded on the AC without the proper documentation indicating that the shipment contained DG. At approximately 16:35 the Cargo Station Chief was doing a spot check of the inter-island clipboards and noticed that the hazmat paperwork previously completed for the compressed gas cylinder was still at the Cargo station at which time the Station Chief tried locate the shipment for which the paperwork belonged to. When the shipment could not be located in the cargo facility it was confirmed by the Cargo Runner that the shipment had been placed on a flight (HA226) which departed at 15:36 for OGG.
column169: Root Cause of the incident was HAZMAT procedures are not clearly defined in the Cargo manual. HA will review and revise as necessary the procedures detailed in the Cargo Manual to ensure that the process of retrieving a DG shipment for transport to the AC is clear and identifies what actions need to be taken when transporting a DG shipment to the AC. A recommendation for improvement to the process will include the placement of a shipping envelope directly on the DG shipment to indicate that the shipment contains DG and proper paperwork is required to accompany the shipment.
column172: Cylinder, a pressure vessel for compressed gases

column168: Original comments:  Upon arrival to station the box was found to be loaded *under* belly flaps against safety guidelines and sideways. internally, paint can is found to have been hit hard on bottom edge and loose rubber seal popped off - all contents leaked and caused multiple other damages. 3 other products damaged on labels.  New Comments: Two one-gallon paint cans and two one-quart paint cans are in the external cardboard box with plastic shoved around and between the smaller cans. cardboard inserts keep the cans from hitting each other, but they push the cans against the external sides of the box. The package was found to be leaking in the trailer as it arrived at our station, tucked underneath the metal belly flaps and on its side despite visible orientation arrows and training that Hazardous Materials are always loaded on Top of the flaps and against the trailer walls. The package appears to be undamaged, but internally one of the 1 gallon paint cans has a large dent in the bottom edge. This appears to have caused the loose rubber/plastic ring around the top of the can to come off entirely, and the paint can lid came off. All contents of the gallon container were lost, and leaked onto multiple other packages, causing a total of seven damages and shipper returns. The remaining three containers have loose rubber/plastic rings, none of which are properly seated or clipped in place to prevent loss of product, however these three also have no damage to the cans outside of minor dents.

Original comments:  Driver went to location of to make drop-off. Noticed the package was leaking and driver refused it. The driver put it in a plastic bag and isolated the package.When he arrived at the station, he notified management. We then put the package into another bag and checked the leaked out liquid for its PH level. It was at a PH level of 13. We put neutralizer down on the spots of the leak and waited for it to neutralize. After the liquid was neutralized, we swept it up and put it in a hazardous material tote along with the smock, gloves, and goggles used to cleanup the spill.  New Comments:

Original comments:  Found hazardous material box on the bottom of the van with the contents missing.WE called the driver and the driver said that he showed it to the customer and the customer accepted the package even though it had been leaking. The customer left the packaging on the lawn and the driver took the packaging and put it on the bottom of his van. We neutralized the packaging, and the spot on the van that it had leaked on.  New Comments:

I WAS CALLED TO A LEAKING CORROSIVE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPILL IN THE OUTBOUND. I ARRIVED WITH MY FULLY STOCKED SPILL CART AND ALL PPE DONNED INCLUDING SILVER SHIELD GLOVES. I SAW A BOX WITH A CORROSIVE DIAMOND LABEL AND UPS SHIPPING PAPERS. USING THE DECISION TREE AND CORROSIVE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET, I TESTED THE PH AND FOUND IT TO BE 13. I APPLIED SODIUM BICARBONATE UNTIL THE PH RETESTED IN THE 6-9 RANGE. I THEN SOLIDIFIED ALL LIQUID WITH CLAY BASED ABSORBENT AND TRANSPORTED IT TO THE DMP WHERE I DISCOVERED THAT IT HAD BEEN REPACKED IN A NON UN SPECIFICATION PACKAGING. I PROCESSED THE REMAINING TWO GALLONS AND A PARTIAL GALLON THROUGH THE DMP PROGRAM AS A LIQUID DUE TO A NOXIOUS ODOR.

column168: ON JUNE 21ST, 2018, THE FOLLOWING SHIPMENT(S) FLEW ON VIRGIN ATLANTIC FLIGHT VS0110 TO MANCHESTER, UK DEPARTING HARTSFIELD-JACKSON INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT (ATL) ETD 2018L. THE NOTIFICATION TO CAPTAIN (NOTOC) WAS COMPLETED BUT WAS NOT PRESENTED NOR SIGNED BY THE CAPTAIN’S KNOWLEDGE (NOTOC) WAS COMPLETED BUT WAS NOT PRESENTED NOR SIGNED BY THE CAPTAIN IN ACCORDANCE WITH IATA AHM 315 AND AHM 352. AS A RESULT, THE AIRCRAFT DEPARTED WITHOUT THE CAPTAIN’S KNOWLEDGE THAT THERE WERE DANGEROUS GOODS ON BOARD. AT APPROXIMATELY, 2200 ON 21 JUNE, I PROCEEDED TO CONTACT THE VS OCC TO MAKE THEM AWARE OF THE ISSUE. THE DUTY DIRECTOR NOTIFIED THE CREW VIA A CARS AND PROVIDED THE VARIES CLASSES OF DG ON BOARD. THE CREW ELECTED TO CONTINUE THE FLIGHT BUT FILED AN AIR SAFETY REPORT (ASR) UPON LANDING.  VS0110 ARRIVED TO MANCHESTER AIRPORT WITHOUT INCIDENT THE FOLLOWING MORNING. THE VIRGIN ATLANTIC STAFF AND GHA WAS MADE AWARE OF THIS DECREPANCY AND FOLLOWED PROCEDURES TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. THE AGENT REPSONSIBLE (GHA) FOR FOLLOWING THE NOTOC WITH HM PROCEDURES IS EMPLOYED BY DELTA AIRLINES – 1600 M H JACKSON RD BLDG. B ATLANTA GA 30354.  DANGEROUS GOODS UN NUMBERS AND CLASS THAT WERE ON BOARD: UN1090 – CLASS 3          UN1993 – CLASS 3           UN3175 – CLASS 4.1 UN1759 – CLASS 8  UN3316 – CLASS 9 UN1950 – CLASS 2.1 UN2037 – CLASS 2.1
column169: PER VIRGIN ATLANTIC’S GHA (DL), FAILURE TO COMMUNICATE BETWEEN THE FIRST AND SECOND SHIFTS WAS THE ROOT CAUSE TO THIS INCIDENT. THE AGENT TAKING THE FLIGHT KITS TO THE AIRCRAFT'S MUST KNOW WHAT INFORMATION IS REQUIRED TO GIVE THE PIC. IN THIS CASE, THE NOTOC WAS NOT PRESENTED TO THE CAPT ON VS0110. DL MGMT. WILL WORK WITH THE AGENTS ON SECURING A MORE EFFICIENT PROCESS FOR PASSING FLIGHTS OVER TO THE NEXT SHIFT.

ALL DRIVER TRAINED TO PAY CLOSE ATTENTION AND INSPECT VALVES, PIPING, ETC. AFTER EACH DELIVERY STOP, BEFORE RE-ENTERING TRANSPORTATION.

column168: Our driver ran off roadway and over turned. We lost about 5500 gallons of NL and 1000 gallons  of ULSD. Weoff loaded remaining product and our unit was towed back to ETC in Montvale.  Action Environmental managed the spill clean up. WEL recovered approximately 5630 gallons of  product and water using a vac truck. A significant majority of that fluid is the gasoline/diesel mix.  Both the WVDOH and the WVDEP visited the site on Saturday. Both agencies apparently expressed  pleasure with everything that has been done. One agency  took random air samples and were  pleased that there were no hits. The contractor has placed several stations of absorbent boom  in the ditch line to catch any remaining product that may be flushed out naturally. The contractor  estimated they excavated 800 ton of soil that has been disposed of in the Greenbrier County Landfill.
column169: Driver was going to be discharged but decide to retire instead. The DriveCam footage indicates that he fell asleep (which he said) or he had some type of medical event occur.

column168: On 06/30/2018, at 1918 hours, personnel in the CSXT Lima Yard discovered PROX 40390, a loaded tank car of Styrene Monomer, Stabilized, leaking from the pressure relief device. The car was isolated and the National Response Center report 1216953 , Ohio EPA, Lima Fire Department, and Ineos Styrolutions Canada LTD were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2018-0630-00139). SUNPRO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the pressure relief device had lifted, more than 50 psig on the car, and shell full of liquid. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Ms. Sue Collins of Ineos, phone (832)-221-7975. The CSX Hazardous Materials Manager responded to the scene, and with SUNPRO transloaded approximately 1,275 liquid gallons of lading into a shipper provided tank truck. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required?  Cause Code: 419 NARRI: 60

column169: SHIPPER NEEDS TO PACK THE PACKAGE THE CORRECT WAY SO THE OBJECT AND ANY PERSON HANDLING IT IS SAFE.

column168: WAS INFORMED ABOUT LEAKER PER MANAGEMENT GRABBED DT, RS, PPE,SPILL CART. FOLLOWED DECISION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET AND PROCEEDED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.
column169: IMPROPER PACKAGING (NO PACKAGING MATERIAL IN BOX) WILL NEED PEANUTS/BUBBLE WRAP/KRAFT PAPER OR SOME KIND OF PACKAGING MATERIALS.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: ARRIVED WITH FULL PPE ON TO FIND PACKAGE SITTING ON RACK(TO BE AUDITED). PACKAGE APPEARED WET ON TOP AND BOTTOM BUT NOTHING HAD LEAKED OUT. FOLLOWED DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR CLEANUP AND CONTAINERIZATION. RETURNED TO DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. ON OPENING PACKAGE FOUND A CONTAINER HAD LEAKED OUT OF CAP ALL OVER INSIDE OF PACKAGE.

THE RELEASE INVOLVED THE RUNOFF WATER GENERATED DURING EXTINGUISHING A VEHICLE FIRE IN THE TRADEBE TRANSPORTATION BOX TRUCK, AND THE COOLING OF A BUILDING IN THE PROXIMITY OF THE BOX VAN. THE RUNOFF WATER IMPACTED THE GRAVEL SURFACE AND DITCH LINE ADJACENT THE LOT. THERE WAS NO WATER POLLUTION OR HARMFUL IMPACTS TO THE ENVIRONMENT.   THE BOX VAN WAS PLACARDED IDENTIFYING ITS CONTENTS OF MULTIPLE CONTAINERS OF MATERIAL, WHICH WERE COMPROMISED AS A RESULT OF THE FIRE. (PLEASE FIND ATTACHED SHIPPING PAPERS FOR REFERENCE)  THE LAPORTE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE. CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES USED A VACUUM TRUCK TO RECOVER APPROXIMATELY 35,000 GALLONS OF FIRE EXTINGUISHING RUN OFF WATER FROM THE IMMEDIATE AREA AND IMPACTED DITCH LINE. CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES ALSO WORKED ON RECOVERY AND SEGREGATION OF THE WASTE FROM THE FIRE DAMAGED TRUCK. ALL WASTE WAS RECOVERED, PENDING DISPOSAL IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS.   THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE.
column169: TRADEBE TRANSPORTATION WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND REINFORCE SAFE HANDLING AND SAFETY GUIDELINES TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: June 13, 2018: At approximately 9:45AM, Conrail Train Crew FO50, along with CR Mechanical Inspector, noted fuming originating from the top of tank car UCLX 461085, containing the residue of Hydrochloric Acid. The car had been switched out from the customer, Univar, at approximately 4-4:3OAM, 6/13/18 and placed in the local serving yard. While the crew was later putting their train together for outbound movement back to Morrisville (PA) Yard, the release was noted. Conrail Risk Manager A. Richter notified shipper of the empty rail car, Univar(car located just outside their facility),^ and they responded to the car. Two representatives of Univar responded while Conrail's A. Richter and M. Little (Trainmaster) were on site. Univar reported the release was originating from the top rubberized closure flanges of the liquid line. They removed the top closure flange, inserted a small gasket, and resecured the top closure flange to that fitting's mounting flange, whereby securing the leak. During conversation with one of the Univar representatives on top of the car after the release was secured, he pointed to a small score on the closure flange's mounting flange; his explanation of the release.

All appropriate departments notified, CN Response Team responded. CN Response Team found the bottom outlet handle to be partially open with the bottom outlet cap less than tool tight. column168: Original comments:  At approximately 8am a package handler discovered the leaking box while unloading a trailer and immediately reported it to an unload manager. The unload manager immediately placed the leaking hazmat in a red bin and called retrieved a maintenance staff member to clean up the spill inside of the trailer. Then the unload manager placed the tote onto the NC belt and asked his fellow unload manager to bring the damaged hazmat to a QA team member. The second manager failed to move the hazmat. AY approximately 8:20 am a QA admin came across the damaged hazmat in the black bin on the NC belt. The QA admin immediately grabbed a red hazmat tote and appropriate PPE and transferred the hazmat liquid and packaging to the red hazmat tote. During the transfer, a small amount of the liquid spilled on the floor. Maintenance was immediately called to clean the spill. The red hazmat tote containing the damaged hazmat and the contaminated black tote were then taken to the hazmat cage to be locked away for safe storage.  New Comments:

column168: THE RESPONDER RECEIVED A CALL FOR A LEAKING PACKAGE IN THE UNLOAD. RESPONDER WEARING ALL APPROPRIATE PPE AND TAKING ALL REQUIRED MATERIALS DETERMINED THAT THE LEAKING PACKAGE WAS A HAZMAT AND RESPONDED ACCORDINGLY. column169: BY THE LOOK OF THE WAY IT LEAKED THE PACKAGE WAS MOST LIKELY LOADED ON ITS SIDE, THOUGH IT DID HAVE ORIENTATION ARROWS. IF IT HAD BEEN LOADED UPRIGHT THE, APPARENTLY FAULTY SEAL ON THE BUCKET CONTAINED IN THE PACKAGE MAY NOT HAVE LEAKED. REVIEWING LOAD METHODS WITH LOADERS TO MAKE SURE THAT THEY UNDERSTAND WHY THEY SHOULD PAY ATTENTION TO ORIENTATION ARROWS MIGHT BE HELPFUL. ALSO, CONTACTING THE SHIPPER TO LET THEM KNOW THAT IT MAY BE HELPFUL THAT, IN THE FUTURE, THEY MAKE SURE THAT THE SEALS ON THEIR SHIPMENTS ARE FUNCTIONING PROPERLY.

column168: FRTL unit was travelling south on a 4 lane divided highway the unit drifted off the road onto the median shoulder and travelled within the median which caused it to reduce speed.  Due to the slope of the median the unit rolled on to its side as it was coming to final rest.   It was confirmed by our emergency response contractor Hepaco that there was no release of product from the cargo tank.  This was confirned by visual inspenction and by a soil surrvey using a OVA meter.   No injuries resulted to our driver and this was a single vehicle accident.  Highway 25 road closure was limitied to only one side of the 4 lane highway allowing traffice to detour. Damamge to the cargo tank was limiitied to external cosmetic tank to the cargo tank shell. This incident is being reported as requested by Galata Tona - Senior Administrative Assistant/Analyst  U.S. Department of Transportation - Contractor - Unispec Enterprises, Inc. Pipeline and Hazardous Materials Safety Administration (PHMSA) .  Note:  Spill amount entered on question 19 (1 liquid gallon).  There was no spill but system would not accept without a number entered in this field.

column168: The operator was finished loading the tank car and during the process of disconnecting the loading hose, he was hammering on the adapter connection for the hose to the extended pipe that was inserted into the liquid valve.  While hammering on the adapter connection the valve handle vibrated open approximately 1/4 turn and when the loading hose threads were loosened then  product leaked out in a vapor gas form.  On site fire brigade responded and made an entry and closed the valve handle and the release stopped. it was calculated that 431 pounds released ,  there was no injury and no other issues.  The valve was not defective and it was secured for transportation.
column169: The facility has made changes to its procedure and is not hammering on the hose connections any longer as well as they are working on a project to conduct better inspections of the loading racks and equipment.  It has also been recommended that they research and possibly replace the types of loading hose connections on the rack side of the process.

column168: The shipment was found due to an odor in the sort. Upon opening the box we found a round metal friction lid can with no Positive Closure. The friction lid had separated from the can. Inside the can was a plastic bottle with a screw on cap. That screw on cap had no Positive Closure either and the screw on cap had backed itself off the bottle.allowing the spill to occur. The plastic bottle was surrounded by absorbent material that did soak up the spill which is why we only found an odor yet not a spill. The lack of any Positive Closure on either the bottle or cans is in violation of 49CFR 173.27(d). The shipment was held pending an FAA inspection. MEM FAA SEECFO Hazmat<Manager Stan Satchell was notified electronically.

The car was isolated and the contents were transferred into another tank car. TIL)(304697 was then cleaned and purged.

column25: WILBUR-ELLIS COMPANY, LLC CHEHALIS BRANCH, BRANCH #
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE IN TRANSIT A HELICOPTER SUPPORT UNIT ROLLED OVER DUE TO A BRAKE FAILURE. AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT 660 GALLONS OF JET FUEL A, 500 GALLONS OF NON-PORTABLE WATER, RELEASED. THE FREE PRODUCT IMPACTED THE ROADSIDE DITCH, ROADWAY, AND MIGRATED ACROSS THE ROADWAY INTO THE ROADSIDE DITCH ON THE OPPOSITE SIDE OF THE ROADWAY. PATRIOT ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (PES) WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. PES ARRIVED AND INSPECTED THE SITE. PES PROCEEDED TO REMOVE THE REMAINING JET FUEL, NON-PORTABLE WATER, AND PESTICIDES FROM THE UNIT. PES DEPLOYED ADDITIONAL ABSORBENT MATERIAL ON THE ROADWAY AS NEEDED. PES RECOVERED THE SPENT ABSORBENT MATERIAL FROM THE ROADWAY. THE SITE WAS SECURED PENDING SITE EXCAVATION ON A LATER DATE.  ON JUNE 11, 2018 PES RETURNED TO THE SITE. PES BEGAN EXCAVATION OF THE CONTAMINATED SOIL FROM THE CONTAMINATED AREA. ON JUNE 12, 2018 PES COMPLETED EXCAVATION OF THE CONTAMINATED SOIL. THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS PLACED INTO ROLL-OFF BINS FOR DISPOSAL. ON JUNE 13TH, 2018 PES BACK FILLED THE REMAINING EXCAVATED AREA. ON JUNE 13TH 2018 EL DORADO COUNTY EMD AND CALTRANS APPROVED COMPLETED CLEAN-UP WORK ON WEST SIDE OF HWY 193. PES COLLECTED SAMPLES ON WEST SIDE OF ROAD PER EL DORADO COUNTY EMD INSTRUCTION. PES COORDINATED DISPOSAL OF THE WASTE GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT.
column169: WILBUR ELLIS COMPANY CONTINUE TO IMPROVE DRIVER SAFETY TRAINING AND REINFORCE SAFETY GUIDELINES AND HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: ON WEDNESDAY, JUNE 13TH IN HNL, A HAWAIIAN AIRLINES MATERIAL SUPPORT AGENT WAS PROCESSING TRANSFER ORDERS TO SHIP TO PHX. THE MATERIAL SUPPORT AGENT PULLED ALL THE PARTS FROM STOCK AND BOXED THE ITEMS (APPROXIMATELY 22 PARTS). THERE WERE TWO DANGEROUS GOODS (DG) PARTS TO SHIP THAT WERE SEPARATED FROM THE NON-DG PARTS. THE PLAN WAS TO SHIP THE TWO DG PARTS SEPARATELY THE FOLLOWING DAY. AT APPROXIMATELY 2240 HST, THE MATERIAL SUPPORT AGENT TOOK THE SHIPMENT TO CARGO TO SIGN THE AIRWAY BILL AND THEN LEFT FOR THE DAY. THE SHIPMENT FLEW ON FLIGHT HA36, WHICH DEPARTED THURSDAY, JUNE 14TH AT 1230 HST. AT APPROXIMATELY 1900 HST, THE MATERIAL SUPPORT AGENT PROCEEDED TO PROCESS THE REMAINING DG PARTS FOR SHIPMENT TO PHX. WHILE PROCESSING THE ORDER, THE MATERIAL SUPPORT AGENT REALIZED THAT ONE OF THE BOXES CONTAINED A NON-DG PART. THIS LED THE MATERIAL SUPPORT AGENT TO BELIEVE THAT A DG PART MAY HAVE BEEN INADVERTENTLY SHIPPED UNDECLARED. THE SHIPMENT ARRIVED IN PHX AT APPROXIMATELY 1830 HST ON THURSDAY, JUNE 18TH. THE SHIPMENT WAS NOT ABLE TO BE RECEIVED AND VERIFIED BY PHX MAINTENANCE UNTIL 0730 HST ON MONDAY, JUNE 18TH. UPON RECEIVING THE SHIPMENT, PHX MAINTENANCE DISCOVERED THAT A DG PART (PN 5262100 – B767 ACTUATOR ASSEMBLY/DOOR OPENING/SNUBBING; UN0276 CARTRIDGES, POWER DEVICE) WAS IN FACT INADVERTENTLY SHIPPED UNDECLARED.
column169: PHYSICAL VERIFICATION AND CONFIRMATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL VIA INSPECTION IS A PROCESS ALREADY IN PLACE AT HAWAIIAN AIRLINES, HOWEVER, THE PROCESS WILL BE IMPROVED TO ENHANCE VISUAL IDENTIFICATION. HAWAIIAN AIRLINES IS ENHANCING LABEL IDENTIFICATION OF ALL HAZMAT ITEMS THROUGHOUT THE INVENTORY SYSTEM BY IMPLEMENTING A CUSTOMIZED RED AND WHITE UNIQUE LABEL MARKED AS “HAZMAT”. ALL HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WILL BE CLEARLY MARKED ON ALL SIDES OF THE CONTAINER WITH THE “HAZMAT” LABEL.  STARTING 8/6/18, ALL INCOMING MATERIAL WILL BE MARKED DURING RECEIVING INSPECTION WITH THE “HAZMAT” LABEL. ALL EXISTING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WILL BE MARKED WITH THE “HAZMAT” LABEL BY 9/30/18. IN ADDITION, A RED “HAZMAT” STAMP WILL BE USED ON ALL DOCUMENTATION AS IT RELATES TO MOVEMENT OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS THROUGH THE NORMAL DAILY OPERATIONS (E.G. RECEIVING, BINNING, PULLING, ISSUING, SHIPPING, ETC.) STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURES WILL BE UPDATED TO REFLECT THE IMPROVED PROCESSES. THIS INCIDENT HAS BEEN BRIEFED TO ALL SUPPLY CHAIN PERSONNEL WITH AN EMPHASIS ON THE IMPORTANCE ON VERIFYING ALL MATERIAL BEFORE COMPLETING THE PACKET PROCESS, AND CONFIRMING THE HAZMAT STATUS OF EACH ITEM TO PREVENT RECURRENCE OF NON-COMPLIANCE EVENTS.

column168: On arriving at the New England Motor Freight Terminal& after making connection to the receiving fitting of the Above Ground Storage Tank (AST) the driver failed to open a ball valve before starting a pump delivery. Pressure built rapidly causing the aluminum"A nut" connection(customer side) to fracture allowing unrestricted flow of product. Driver reacted immediately shutting down product supply and pump, then treating affected area to prevent spread of product using absorbent materials and spill pads. Majority of product remained on asphalt surface, but unknown amount entered grass/dirt area adjacent to paved surface, flowing under a fence line and toward a wooded area. HEPACO(spill contractor) responded to treat and clean up spilled product and contaminated materials. Original estimate of 150 lost gallons reasonably reduced to near 100 gallons after hoses drained and trailer tank compartment gauged. PA DEP(Evan Elliott) was notified of spill at time of release. Upon review the spill contractor returned and handled additional re-mediation where soil was impacted as directed. As of July 2nd, 2018 clean-up of area is done. Attached is the report from the Spill Response Contractor(HEPACO) along with pictures for the area of the spill. BOL and MSDS all also attached.
column169: Review of loss event with driver involved, discussion with other employees who are involved in pump operation to improve delivery procedure.

IN THE COURSE OF DOING SO, THE STORAGE TANK OVERFILLED WHICH RESULTED IN APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION TO BE RELEASED. A MAJORITY OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS ISOLATED IN THE TANK’S SECONDARY CONTAINMENT. THE CUSTOMER HAD SIGNED THE LOAD PAPERWORK GIVING IN THE DRIVER CLEARANCE TO INITIATE THE DELIVERY AND CONFIRMING THAT THE LOAD WOULD FIT IN THE STORAGE TANK. CLEAN HARBORS RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: PART VII-RECOMMENDATIONS/ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT RECURRENCE THE CUSTOMER WILL NEED TO VERIFY THAT THERE IS ADEQUATE STORAGE IN THEIR TANK TO HOLD THE VOLUME OF PRODUCT BEING DELIVERED.

column168: THE BXI, LLC DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO LOAD CONDENSATE INTO HIS TRAILER. IN THE COURSE OF DOING SO, A GASKET ON THE HOSE FAILED AND APPROXIMATELY 7 GALLONS OF CONDENSATE WAS RELEASED. EMS ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION WHICH REMAINS ONGOING.
column169: BXI, LLC WILL MAKE THE NECESSARY REPAIRS TO THE HOSE GASKET TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE.

column168: A Veolia employee arrived at the Louisville, KY 10-day intransit facility to utilize a pick up truck for another job.  The employee found the truck was full of containers so he began to off-load the truck.  As he was off-loading the truck he noticed one container was sitting on its top.  The container appeared to have fallen during transportation.  As the employee picked up the container, he noticed the top was wet.  He then inspected the truck and noticed two small pools of liquid.  There was approximately two milliliters of liquid in the bed of the truck.  The label on the box stated the box contained Hydrochloric Acid Solution.  The employee then overpacked the container and cleaned up the 2 mL spill in the bed of the truck.
column169: The Veolia employees working in the Louisville office were retrained on load securement and checking the load.  The topic of proper packaging of lab pack waste material was also reviewed during the training.  The employees need to be sure the load is always secure before leaving a customer site and any time they stop during transportation.

column168: Driver was unloading tanker compartment in to underground tank at C-store. Wrong tank had been selected and was overfilled. Fuel spilled out of a fuel pump dispenser out a relief valve located under the pump handle. it is unknown the exact amount of spillage at this time as we are still investigating the cause, the tank dimensions/size and duration of spill. Currently we are estimating the spill at less than 120 gallons. At the time of the spill the area was experiencing a large downpour of approximately 1.25 inches of rain in less than an hour. The material that was spilled was washed into the gutters and flowed into the storm drain which does outfall  into the Forest River approximately 1/3 of a mile South. After the incident there was no material/sheen seen in the outfall area or the river downstream for at 1/4 mile. Station Manager is also the City fire chief and there was no danger or materials to cleanup. The Tanker did not fail. The driver unloaded into a wrong underground tank and the excess materials spilled out of the pump at the C store station. The station is investigation how this could have happened and if anything is wrong with the pumps or tank venting system. We are following up on the investigation on this matter as well. once the investigation is complete will have a better estimate of how much product was actually lost. Only costwill be the loss of the product. Does not seem like it is as much as is estimated currently.
column169: We will be re-marking the tanks with an improved system of numbering tanks and identifying them on a map and also reminding drivers to consistently stick tanks to verify volumes.

column168: Driver was delivering a drum of Soidum Hypochlorite. Upon utilizing his manual drum dolly to transport the drum to the rear of the trailer for the customer to remove it from the delivery vehicle, the drum disengaged from the drum dolly and fell off of the back of the delivery trailer onto the pavement below causing approximately a 9" split in the drum and releasing approximately 180 pounds of material. Driver and customer personnel immediately contained the spill with spill socks and placed the damaged drum into a 95 gallon overpack drum carried on the delivery trailer.
column169: An internal investigation was conducted and it was determined that the manual drum dolly utilized by the driver was partially defective. This defect caused the drum of material to disengage from the drum dolly. The drums dolly has been replaced with a brand new model and all other drum dollies have been inspected to ensure they are free from defects to prevent recurrence of this type of incident.

column168: NORFOLK SOUTHERN PERSONNEL REPORTED A STRONG ODOR AROUND TANK CAR GATX57030. UPON INSPECTION BY A CONTRACTOR, THE ODOR WAS FOUND TO BE COMING FROM THE MAN-WAY. PRODUCT RESIDUE WAS FOUND ON THE MAN-WAY NOZZLE AND THE MAN-WAY GASKET WAS FOUND TO BE DETERIORATED. THE MAN-WAY GASKET WAS REPLACED AND THE MAN-WAY SECURED. THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORT.

I, JOHN VERGIS ENVIRONMENTAL OFFICER, FOR THE WLE WAS CALLED AT 1543 HRS. BY THE WLE BREWSTER YARDMASTER ABOUT A POSSIBLE LEAKING CAR CBTX 736943, NATURAL GASOLINE, ON THE EAST END OF 28 TRACK IN BREWSTER. THIS CAR WAS REPORTED BY THE CAR INSPECTOR AS HAVING AN ODOR. I ARRIVED AT ABOUT 1730 HRS. AND CLIMBED THE TOP OF THE CAR BUT COULD NOT FIND ANY PROBLEMS. I CHECKED SURROUNDING CARS AND FOUND THAT THE CAR ON THE EAST END OF THIS CAR, TANK CAR TAEX 30165 WAS THE ONE THAT WAS HAVING AN ODOR COMING FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AFTER I CHECKED IT WITH MY METER. I COULD NOT TELL IF THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE WAS LEAKING OR NOT BECAUSE I WOULD GET A HIT AROUND IT FROM TIME TO TIME BUT NOT EVERY TIME. I TOOK THE COVER OFF OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE AND CHECKED IT MORE THOROUGHLY BUT COULD NOT QUITE TELL. I PUT SNOOP AROUND THE BASE AND COULDN’T FIND ANYTHING OBVIOUS. I PUT SNOOP AROUND THE BASE OF THE GAUGING DEVICE ALSO BUT COULD NOT FIND A LEAK. NEITHER THE LIQUID VALVE OF THE VAPOR VALVE WAS LEAKING. I KEPT GETTING A HIT ON MY METER EVERY TIME I PUT THE WAND BETWEEN THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE AND THE GAUGING DEVICE. I TOOK THE CAP OFF OF THE GAUGING DEVICE AND THE METER WENT OFF INSTANTLY. I TRIED TO OPERATE THE DEVICE AND FOUND THAT THE DEVICE WAS FULL OF LIQUID WHICH ENDED UP BEING GASOLINE. I TOOK THE GAUGING ROD OUT AND WAS ABLE TO HEAR VAPOR HISSING FROM INSIDE THE TUBE INDICATING THAT THE TUBE MIGHT BE CRACKED. I CHECKED THE PRESSURE ON THE CAR AND IT WAS ONLY 1 POUND. I PUT EVERYTHING BACK TOGETHER AND TIGHTENED THE GAUGING DEVICE CAP TOOL TIGHT TO STOP THE LEAK SINCE THE O RING WAS IN GOOD ORDER. I REMOVED SEAL NUMBER 202903 FROM THE LID OF THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING. I MADE A CHEMTREC REPORT AND NOTIFIED MARKWEST FOR THEM TO MAKE A DECISION ON GETTING A PROPER REPAIR MADE TO THE CAR. THE CAR WAS SET OUT OF THE TRAIN AND SENT TO THE SHOP. ON 7-16-2018 I MET WITH ZACHARY CAMPBELL FROM THE MARKWEST WESTLAND PLANT AND SUNPRO TO REVIEW THE CAR AND VERIFY THE LEAK AND THEN TRANSLOAD INTO CAR CBTX 742861. WE VERIFIED THAT THE GAUGING DEVICE WAS LEAKING AS WE COULD SEE IT WITH PUTTING SNOOP INSIDE THE TUBE. WE COULD NOT TELL IF WAS A CRACK OR A BAD GASKET. CAR WILL BE CLEANED AND REPAIRED.
column169: I DON’T BELIEVE ANYONE DID ANYTHING WRONG NOR WAS THERE NEGLECT IN SECURING THIS CAR FOR SHIPMENT.

column168: On arriving at the New England Motor Freight Terminal & after making connection to the receiving fitting of the Above Ground Storage Tank(AST) the driver failed to open a ball valve before starting a pump delivery. Pressure built rapidly causing the aluminum"A nut" connection(customer side) to fracture allowing unrestricted flow of product. Driver reacted immediately shutting down product supply and pump. then treating affected area to prevent spread of product using absorbent materials and spill pads. Majority of product remained on asphalt surface but unknown amount entered grass/dirt area adjacent to paved surface. flowing under a fence line and toward a wooded area. HEPACO(spill contractor) responded to treat and clean up spilled product and contaminated materials. Original estimate of 150 lost gallons reasonably reduced to near 100 gallons after hoses drained and trailer tank compartment gauged. PA DEP(Evan Elliott) was notified of spill at time of release. Upon review the spill contractor returned and handled additional re-mediation where soil was impacted as directed. As of July 2nd. 2018 clean-up of area is done. Attached is the report from the Spill Response Contractor(HEPACO) along with pictures for the area of the spill. BOL and MSDS all also attached.

column168: PART VI-DESCRIPTION OF EVENTS AND PACKAGE FAILURE THE DISTTECH, LLC DRIVER WAS PREPARING TO DELIVER HYDROCHLORIC ACID INTO THE CUSTOMER’S STORAGE TANK. IN THE COURSE OF DOING SO, THE DRIVER FAILED TO BE CERTAIN THAT ALL OF THE VALVES WERE CLOSED ON THE TRAILER. WHEN HE INTRODUCED AIR INTO THE TRAILER, APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID WAS RELEASED FROM THE OPEN VALVE. PETROLEUM RECOVERY SERVICES RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: PART VII-RECOMMENDATIONS/ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT RECURRENCE DISTTECH, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN ENFORCE SAFE LOADING/UNLOADING POLICIES AND PROCEDURES.

column168: On 6/1/18 at approximately 10:00 am a Venezia Transport tanker truck was getting set up to receive a load of heated coal tar. As the IMTT Chemical Operator was moving the fall protection ladder into place it accidentally struck the spiller pipe which in tum knocked the bucket, which hangs on the end of the arm, over causing coal tar to spill onto the side of the tanker truck. The IMTT Chemical Operator immediately contacted his supervisor who in tum contacted US Ecology(IMTT's OSRO) to clean up the side of the truck. When this was complete the loading operation continued without incident.
column169: Upon investigation IMTT determined that the loading arm which was recently installed was not level and when the IMTT Chemical Operator went to move the fall protection stairs it struck the loading arm. The rack was taken out of service so the loading arm can be re-aligned. The rack is now back in service.

column168: This 10 piece shipment was selected by customs and tested with some equipment to test chemicals. No report or written documentation was provided but it was verbally shared with FedEx management that it was suspected to be a Division 5.1. The Safety Data Sheet obtained from the shipper clearly stated this was nonhazardous. I reported this to our FAA PHI's with the intention to request an FAA agent investigate the shipment as a possible undeclared DG based on the testing from customs. However, due to some local Anchorage miscommunication with the spill office, since it had cleared customs and the Safety Data Sheet stated it was nonhazardous they failed to hold the shipment for FAA inspection and sent it through the system. It is unknown whether or not it was actually a dangerous goods or not- whether the test results from customs were wrong or the SDS had an error in it.
column169: No comments provided

column168: Freight shifted while in transit due to improper blocking and bracing. The shift in freight caused damage to container resulting in a release of product. Dock personnel recovered released product with absorbents and placed into a container for proper disposal.
column169: Provide additional training to material handlers to ensure that they are implementing proper freight handling techniques and are able to recognize and prevent potential future incidents.

column168: Package was turned on the side and gas started to leak from the container. The  package was placed upright but the outer package was then opened to inspected what was leaking. The inside container had a non-flammable gas label on it. Once this was discovered the package was held for the FAA but was released to shipper with pictures taken because of the high value of contents and because they would be ruined if not kept cold. Ryan Pohlke and Steve Redeker were contacted with the FAA by phone and email.

column168: On 06/29/2018 at 2055 hours CSXT personnel in the Boyles Yard(Birmingham, AL) discovered PXCX17012, a loaded tank car of Hydrogen Peroxide leaking from top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Peroxychem LLC was notified. Marion Environmental(MEI), a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the rupture disk to have ruptured. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Peroxychem(Ralph Mikida 215-692-4661). MEI received a replacement rupture disk from Peroxychem and replaced the rupture disk. This car was not found to be overloaded. Car was released. NAR Cause Code: 1004 Tarrant, AL- 06/29/18-PXCX17012- Hydrogen Peroxide

column168: DURING ROUTINE FACILITY STAGING OPERATIONS, A TRANSPORT TRAILER WAS IDENTIFIED TO HAVE HAD A RELEASE. IN APPROPRIATE PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, VERIFIED THROUGH INTERNAL HEALTH AND SAFETY DEPARTMENTS, TRAINED FACILITY PERSONNEL ENTERED THE TRAILER TO IDENTIFY THE COMPROMISED CONTAINER. ONCE IDENTIFIED, PERSONNEL WERE SUCCESSFUL IN SAFELY PLACING THE CONTAINER INTO A UN SPECIFICATION SALVAGE POLY DRUM AND REMEDIATION OF THE TRANSPORT TRAILER. THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED TO THE TRANSPORT TRAILER ONLY; NO LAND, SOIL, WATER WAYS OR STORM DRAINS WERE IMPACTED BY THE RELEASE. THE CONTAINER WAS SENT TO ITS FINAL DESTINATION DISPOSAL FACILITY WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.
column169: FACILITY PERSONNEL AND MANAGEMENT HELD A SAFETY STAND DOWN MEETING WITH AN EMPHASIS ON PALLET INSPECTION AND INTEGRITY. IT HAS BEEN COMMUNICATED WIDELY TO CHANGE OUT PALLETS AS NECESSARY, WHEN INTEGRITY IS QUESTIONABLE.

column168: AT 0106 ET ERTS was contacted by caller XPO Logisitics Larry Longbons of the XLA facility regarding a spill. Caller reported he opened trailer and saw puddle on floor of trailer #3115801. Caller reported a 55gal drum leaking about 2 cups of UN3082 "Dub Synersol Isodecyl Neopentanoate" of material to the trailer floor . Caller reports the drum appears to be damaged due to a manufacturers defect with the drum. Caller reported spill has seeped into wood of trailer floor and dried. ERTS could not located direct SDS to determine cleanup procedure and product safety. ERTS working to dispatch contractor. ERTS made contact with Future Environmental , however contact was also made with Sunpro for response to spill. Sunpro provided ETA of 545. ERTS will upload BOL, create Titan, contact Chem Trec. DOT 5800 report required.

A VEOLIA EMPLOYEE WAS OFF-LOADING CONTAINERS FROM A STRAIGHT TRUCK A THE VEOLIA 10 DAY IN-TRANSIT FACILITY LOCATED IN BLAINE, MN. THE EMPLOYEE WAS USING A FORKLIFT WITH A DRUM GRABBER ATTACHMENT. WHILE EXITING ONTO THE DOCK, THE DRUM GRABBER ATTACHMENT MADE CONTACT WITH A METAL DRUM THAT WAS LOCATED ON THE DOCK. THIS CONTACT RESULTED IN A SMALL HOLE IN THE SIDE OF THE DRUM APPROXIMATELY 1 CUP (8 OUNCES) OF MATERIAL LEAKED ONTO THE FLOOR. THE MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED, CLEANED UP AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM ALONG WITH THE DAMAGED DRUM FOR TRANSPORTATION TO THE DISPOSAL SITE.
column169: THE INCIDENT WAS REVIEWED WITH THE VEOLIA FIELD EMPLOYEES AND THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS RETRAINED ON THE PROPER SAFE OPERATION OF THE FORKLEFT.

column168: Norfolk Southern personnel reported tank car PPRX33915 venting from the PRD. Upon inspection by a contractor, the car was found with excess pressure. The tank car was flared down to relieve the excess pressure and allow the PRD to re-seat. The shipper determined excess nitrogen pressure from the previous off-load was not removed prior to reloadlng the car. The shipper agreed to handle cars off-loaded with nitrogen differently going forward. This was the second tank car of propylene with this issue in 2 days. A third tank car TEIX153317 was returned to the shipper as a precaution.

column168: AT 1555 ET ON 6/21/2018, ERTS WAS NOTIFIED BY XPO LOGISTICS REGARDING A CARGO RELEASE. THE CALLER STATED THAT DUE TO IMPROPER SHIPPING FROM A PRIOR TERMINAL APPROXIMATELY 5 OZ. OF UN2582, “FERRIC CHLORIDE 42BE”, 8, III RELEASED FROM A (1) 55-GALLON POLY DRUM. THE CALLER STATED THAT THE RELEASED PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED TO THE TOP PORTION OF THE DRUM, WRAPPED UNDER A LAYER OF PLASTIC. NO PALLETS OR OTHER MATERIAL WAS DAMAGED. THE CALLER BELIEVES THE PRIOR TERMINAL DID NOT FASTEN BOLT DOWN TO THE DRUM THEREBY SPILLING SOME OF THE PRODUCT ON TOP OF THE DRUM. ERTS COULD NOT LOCATED THE SDS, AND THE CALLER DID NOT HAVE A POLY OVER-PACK AT THE TERMINAL TO CONTAINERIZE THE DRUMS, THEREFORE A CONTRACTOR WAS DISPATCHED. AT 1650 ET ON 06/21/2018, ERTS CONTACTED H20 ENVIRONMENTAL WHO GAVE AN ETA OF 2 AND A HALF HOURS (1940ET) DUE TO THE DISTANCE (92 MILES FROM SITE), AND HAVING TO PULL A SUPERVISOR FROM ANOTHER JOB. THE CONTRACTOR BROUGHT A POLY OVER-PACK TO CONTAINERIZE THE DRUM.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS, SOILS OR WATERWAYS REPORTED TO HAVE BEEN IMPACTED BY THE RELEASE. THERE IS NO REGULATORY REPORTING REQUIRED FOR THIS RELEASE BECAUSE SPILLS IN TRAILERS, CONCRETE DOCKS, CONTAINMENT AREAS, INSIDE BUILDINGS ARE NOT ENVIRONMENT AND NOT CONSIDERED REPORTABLE.

column168: DRIVER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF RAISING THE TARPED ROLL-OFF BOX ON THE TRAILER IN PREPARATION FOR DROPPING IT AT VEOLIA’S 10 DAY IN-TRANSIT YARD WHEN HE NOTICED BLACK LIQUID SPILLING OUT THE TOP OF THE ROLL-OFF BOX. APPROXIMATELY 40 GALLONS OR 400 POUNDS OF MATERIAL WAS SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND. THE DRIVER LOWERED THE BOX BACK DOWN ONTO THE TRAILER AND NOTIFIED VEOLIA FACILITY PERSONNEL OF THE SPILL.  THE MATERIAL WAS A F039 CODED FILTER CAKE FROM A PRE-RCRA CLOSED LANDFILL.  THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WHICH INCLUDED DIGGING UP THE IMPACTED SOIL DOWN TO THE PLASTIC LINER LOCATED ON THE 10-DAY YARD. THE BOX WAS SENT FOR IMMEDIATE PROCESSING AT THE VEOLIA INCINERATOR AND DUMPED INTO THE APPROPRIATE WASTE PIT. APPARENTLY DURING TRANSPORTATION, THE ENTRAINED WATER IN THE FILTER CAKE SEPARATED OUT CREATING A LIQUID LAYER ON TOP AND SOLID LAYER ON BOTTOM.
column169: RECOMMENDATION: AT TIME OF SHIPMENT, IT WAS UNKNOWN THAT THE HIGH WATER CONTENT OF THE FILTER CAKE WOULD CAUSE THE MATERIAL TO SEPARATE INTO TWO LAYERS DURING TRANSPORTATION. THIS RESULTED IN WATER RISING TO THE TOP AND THE SOLIDS SETTLING AT THE BOTTOM. FUTURE SHIPMENTS OF THIS MATERIAL WILL BE DONE IN THE VACUUM BOX OR ANOTHER CONTAINER THAT WOULD PROVIDE ADEQUATE PROTECTION FROM LIQUID SPILLAGE DURING TRANSPORTATION. ALSO, PERSONNEL WHO ARE INVOLVED IN TRANSPORTING THIS TYPE OF MATERIAL WILL BE RETRAINED ON THE ISSUES FACED WITH TRANSPORTING THIS TYPE OF MATERIAL AND THE APPROPRIATE CONTAINERS FOR SHIPPING THIS MATERIAL.

column168: ON 6/30/2018 AT APPROXIMATELY 08:00, KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY'S ENVIRONMENTAL & HAZMAT DEPARTMENT RECEIVED NOTICE THAT UTLX 210942 (UN1268 / PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S.) WAS LEAKING FROM THE MANWAY WHEN MOVED. A RAILROAD QUALIFIED RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS MOBILIZED TO RESPOND.  UPON INVESTIGATION, UTLX 210942 WAS FOUND TO HAVE 4 OF THE 8 MANWAY SWING BOLT LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. THE MANWAY LID WAS OPENED AND GASKET INSPECTED, GASKET FOUND TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION. ALL VALVING WAS INSPECTED AND NO OTHER DEFICIENCIES WERE FOUND. SPILLAGE WAS ESTIMATED AT 1 GALLON AND WAS CONTAINED TO THE CAR WITH NO IMPACT TO GROUND OBSERVED. THE MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE SECURED TOOL TIGHT AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED BACK INTO TRANSPORTATION.  FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A 'BULK' SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALVE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARI TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE BY AND LARGE, PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A. PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT-CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE(S) OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS. (PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY, P.O. column168: UPON ARRIVAL TO THE FINAL DESTINATION DISPOSAL FACILITY, A CONTAINER USED FOR TRANSPORT WAS IDENTIFIED AS HAVING RESIDUE ON THE OUTSIDE. A WELD IN THE CONTAINER WAS FURTHER IDENTIFIED AS HAVING BEEN COMPROMISED AND ALLOWING MATERIAL TO RELEASE THROUGH IT. THE RELEASED MATERIAL WAS PRIMARY CONTAINED TO THE BOX; A CONTAINMENT BUCKET WAS PLACED BENEATH TO PREVENT THE MATERIAL FROM IMPACTING THE GROUND. A MINIMAL AMOUNT REACHED GRAVEL; NO WATER WAYS OR STORM DRAINS WERE IMPACTED. IN APPROPRIATE PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, VERIFIED THROUGH THE INTERNAL HEALTH AND SAFETY DEPARTMENT, A RESPONSE TEAM WAS DISPATCHED TO ASSIST IN REMEDIATION OF THE CONTAINER. THE DISPOSAL FACILITY ACCEPTED THE CONTAINER AND DISPOSED OF THE MATERIAL WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.
column169: THE ACCOUNT MANAGER FOR THIS GENERATOR SPOKE IN DETAIL WITH THE GENERATOR ABOUT THIS RELEASE, THE PROCESS IN WHICH THE MATERIAL WAS GENERATED AND THE NECESSARY MEANS TO ENSURE THE MATERIAL IS FREE OF ALL LIQUIDS PRIOR TO TRANSPORTATION. THE PROCESS ITSELF AND THE PROCESSING CONTRACTOR ADJUSTED THE POLYMERS IN THE RECIPE AND HAVE BEEN SUCCESSFUL IN REMOVING ALL FREE LIQUID FROM THE MATERIAL FOR ALL BATCHES MOVING FORWARD. ADDITIONALLY, THE CONTAINER ITSELF WAS RED TAGGED AND PLACED OUT OF SERVICE.

column168: HONEYWELL GENERATED (4) 551H1 POLY DRUMS OF WATER RINSES CONTAINING TRACE ETHANOL, TOLUENE, SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION pH 9-11 RANGE. THE DRUMS WERE PUT OUT ON THE HAZARDOUS WASTE PAD ON 5/30/18 AND THEIR BUNGS WERE LEFT LOOSE BY HONEYWELL PERSONNEL DUE TO SOME OF THEM OFF GASSING AND BUILDING PRESSURE. THE BUNGS WERE LEFT LOOSE UNTIL THE AFTERNOON OF 6/1/18 WHEN VEOLIA TORQUED THE BUNGS CLOSED AND SHIPPED THEM OFF SITE TO THE VEOLIA 10 DAY IN-TRANSIT FACILITY. THE DRUMS DID NOT BUILD ANY NOTICEABLE PRESSURE WHILE VEOLIA WAS MOVING THEM ONTO THE TRUCK AT HONEYWELL. THE DRUMS WERE UNLOADED ONTO A TRAILER AT VEOLIA, 300 WOODWARD AVE. AROUND 4:45 PM. AT APPROXIMATELY 7:00 PM THE DRUMS WERE RE-CHECKED AND IT WAS NOTICED THAT THE DRUMS WERE UNDER A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRESSURE. IT WAS NOT AN UNCOMMON AMOUNT OF PRESSURE BUILD UP FOR FLAMMABLE DRUMS BEING IN A HOT/HUMID ENVIRONMENT. ON SATURDAY, A VEOLIA EMPLOYEE RETURNED TO THE OFFICE AROUND 5:45 PM TO RECHECK THE DRUMS. WHEN CHECKED, LIQUID WAS OBSERVED ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. ONE OF THE BLUE POLY DRUMS FROM HONEYWELL WAS UNDER A LOT OF PRESSURE AND ON HAD SPLIT WIDE OPEN AND HAD A HOLE IN IT THE SIZE OF A QUARTER.  THE SPLIT DRUM LOST ABOUT 30-35 GALLONS OF LIQUID TO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. VEOLIA EMPLOYEES OVERPACKED THE DRUM AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL.
column169: VEOLIA WILL FOLLOW UP WITH HONEYWELL'S CHEMICAL ENGINEERS TO DETERMINE WHAT MAY HAVE CAUSED THE PRESSURE BUILD-UP/OFF-GASSING. FIND OUT IF NEW OR USED CONTAINERS WITH OTHER RESIDUES WERE USED TO FILL THE DRUMS. FIND OUT WHETHER THEY HAVE HAD ISSUES WITH THIS WASTE IN THE PAST AND IF THEY KNOW WHY THE DRUMS ARE BUILDING UP SO MUCH PRESSURE. LOOK INTO THE POSSIBILITY OF STORING WASTE FOR A LONGER DURATION AT THE CUSTOMER SITE PRIOR TO SHOPPING AND USE VENTED CAPS TO AVOID OVER-PRESSURIZATION.  VEOLIA NOTIFIED HONEYWELL THAT ANY FUTURE DRUMS OBSERVED TO BE BUILDING PRESSURE WILL NOT BE ACCEPTED BY VEOLIA UNTIL PRESSURE IS SAFE IN DRUMS AND/OR THE MATERIAL IS NOT REACHING.

AT THE COMPLETION OF BOARDING ON FLIGHT #608, THE CABIN BEGAN TO SMELL OF AN ELECTRICAL BURNING ODOR. IT WAS UNCLEAR AS TO ITS ORIGIN, SO THE CAPTAIN DECIDED TO MAKE A DECISION TO DEPLANE "EXPEDITIOUSLY" BUT NON-EMERGENCY. THE PASSENGERS WERE INSTRUCTED TO LEAVE THEIR BELONGINGS AND DEPLANE STEADILY THROUGH THE L1 DOOR INTO THE JETBRIDGE AND CARRY ON TO THE TERMINAL. WHILE DEPLANING, A PASSENGER FROM THE AFT OF THE AIRCRAFT NOTICED THAT A BAG (CONTAINING THE TABLET) UNDER THE SEAT IN ROW 11 WAS SMOKING. THE PASSENGER PICKED THE TABLET UP AND HANDED IT TO THE LEAD FA WHO QUICKLY PUT IT INTO THE JETBRIDGE WHERE GROUND STAFF EXTINGUISHED THE SMOKING ITEM. THE PASSENGERS WERE KEPT IN THE TERMINAL WHILE GROUND AIR WAS PASSED THROUGH THE CABIN TO TRY TO DISSIPATE THE ELECTRICAL BURNING SMELL. ALLEGIANT MAINTENANCE TENDED TO THE AIRCRAFT TO CHECK FOR ANY CONCERNS, FOUND NONE AND CLEARED IT FOR TRAVEL. PASSENGER WAS ALLOWED TO TRAVEL ON THE SWAPPED FLIGHT AS IT WAS DETERMINED TO BE A NO-FAULT SITUATION.

column168: Driver was doing a pump off load unloading at Oxford Oil, it is possible driver may not have had the dog ears fully clamped on one side of the hose to pump. Spill was primarily contained in retaining area but what ran over was diverted and stopped by spill pads.
column169: We took driver back to the scene /spill area and reenacted his actions leading up to the spill. We also talked with the manager at Oxford Oil about the excessive vibration of the pump .  The driver did realize where he failed and made his mistake .  We retrained him in these areas.
